<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-05-18T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-05-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="364" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d364">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/1191:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-05-18T13:00:00+08:00">May 18, 1933—1
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 18—4:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>447. Reuter from Canton today: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Southwest Political Council has telegraphed to Foreign Office in
                                    Nanking and to Chinese Ambassador in Moscow urging that
                                    everything possible be done to prevent proposed sale of Chinese
                                    Eastern Railway by Russia. Council has also decided to telegraph
                                    to Central Party authorities urging them to send big army to
                                    safeguard Tientsin and Peiping against possible Japanese
                                    invasion of that area.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>